"},{"pid":"60a93fdd3eec763d5efb9a49bf771f3a952bee54","tid":2360163,"uid":18358,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":1,"replyTime":"2021-01-13T06:15:58.000Z","msg":"係連登, 點解想正經傾個時就無人<br />\n<br />\nHow about nitron."},{"pid":"d392b77cc559a3b7689488a77c5b6d62383b3e93","tid":2360163,"uid":365509,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2021-01-13T06:26:45.000Z","msg":"KW Clubsport"},{"pid":"a3804adecfbbc933374629de3b842abd125b8ccc","tid":2360163,"uid":18358,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"quote":{"pid":"22920a5170fbdee9e471d54f9f5eb92944476c6f","tid":2360163,"uid":18358,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":1,"replyTime":"2021-01-12T11:10:37.000Z","msg":"YCW Hong Kong？"},"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2021-01-13T06:54:47.000Z","msg":"見鬼佬YCW 計晒數先組裝避震...<br />\n唔知香港YCW 有無一樣咁做...<br />\n<br />\n<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1VRo_xPFArVgCHhcUVU23hGgMMF4ui8UvX7BwusPj5yw/edit#gid=1297709474\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fdocs.google.com%2Fspreadsheets%2Fd%2F1VRo_xPFArVgCHhcUVU23hGgMMF4ui8UvX7BwusPj5yw%2Fedit%23gid%3D1297709474&d=3UqZ%2FPYEUq8PtOmaimGdDf7c%2B9HD3JYLAdxAiSxEDXo%3D&h=98e13686\" data-auto-link target=\"_blank\">https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1VRo_xPFArVgCHhcUVU23hGgMMF4ui8UvX7BwusPj5yw/edit#gid=1297709474</a>"},{"pid":"f58f2389bfb8f0d4f8a966d7aa290be8c7140c77","tid":2360163,"uid":18358,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2021-01-13T07:05:27.000Z","msg":"Ride Comfort<br />\n<br />\n The quality referred to as &ldquo;ride comfort&rdquo; is affected by a variety of factors, including high frequency vibrations, body booming, body roll and pitch, as well as the vertical spring action normally associated with a smooth ride. If the vehicle is noisy, if it rolls excessively in turns, or lurches and pitches during acceleration and braking, or if the body produces a booming resonance, occupants will experience an &ldquo;uncomfortable ride.&rdquo;<br />\nThe ride quality normally associated with the vehicle&rsquo;s response to bumps is a factor of the relatively low frequency bounce and rebound movements of the suspension system. Following a bump, the undamped suspension (without shocks) of a vehicle will experience a series of oscillations that will cycle according to the natural frequency of the system. Ride is perceived as most comfortable when the natural frequency is in the range of 60 to 90 cycles per minute (CPM), or about 1 Hz to 1.5 Hz. When the frequency approaches 120 CPM (2 Hz), occupants perceive the ride as harsh. Consequently, the suspension of the average family sedan will have a natural frequency of about 60 to 90 CPM. A high-performance sports car will have a stiffer suspension with a natural frequency of about 120 to 150 CPM (2 to 2.5 Hz).<br />\n<br />\n<a href=\"https://rqriley.com/automobile-ride-handling-and-suspension-design-and-implications-for-low-mass-vehicles/\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Frqriley.com%2Fautomobile-ride-handling-and-suspension-design-and-implications-for-low-mass-vehicles%2F&d=3UqZ%2FPYEUq8PtOmaimGdDf7c%2B9HD3JYLAdxAiSxEDXo%3D&h=3473fc38\" data-auto-link target=\"_blank\">https://rqriley.com/automobile-ride-handling-and-suspension-design-and-implications-for-low-mass-vehicles/</a>"}]}